Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget the async dialog
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **hardware/OS back button** (Android). It does *not* fire for the Shell navbar back arrow.

**3. Replace the navbar back arrow with a custom "Cancel" button**

Disable Shell's built-in back button and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
    x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
    Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
            IsVisible="true"
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "Discard changes and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior` controls the **navbar** back button (icon, text, command).
- `OnBackButtonPressed` controls the **hardware** back button (Android/tizen).
- You need **both** to fully guard against accidental navigation.
